  <h1>About FreelancePricingCalc</h1>

  <h2>Our Mission</h2>
  <p>Most freelancers underprice their services. Not because their work isn't valuable, but because they don't account for the full cost of self-employment when setting rates. They look at their former employee salary, divide by 2,000 hours, and set their hourly rate at something that sounds "fair" — without accounting for self-employment taxes, health insurance, retirement, non-billable time, business overhead, or the income uncertainty premium that independent work demands.</p>
  <p>The result: a freelance rate that looks competitive but actually generates less take-home income than employment would, with more stress and less job security. FreelancePricingCalc exists to fix that. We help freelancers calculate the rate they actually need — not the rate that sounds nice — based on what they want to take home, what their business actually costs, and how many hours they can realistically bill.</p>

  <h2>Who This Tool Is For</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>New freelancers setting their rates for the first time</li>
    <li>Experienced freelancers wondering whether their current rates are actually sustainable</li>
    <li>Employees considering going independent who want to understand what hourly rate they'd need to match their current total compensation</li>
    <li>Freelancers preparing to raise their rates and wanting a data-backed framework for the conversation</li>
    <li>Anyone who wants to understand the real cost comparison between freelance and employee economics</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <p>You enter your desired annual take-home income, your self-employment overhead costs (health insurance, retirement contributions, tools, professional liability insurance), and your expected billable hours per week. The calculator works backward to the gross hourly or monthly rate you need to achieve that income goal, after accounting for self-employment tax (15.3%), estimated federal and state income tax, and business overhead. It also shows you how your calculated rate compares to market benchmarks for your specialty.</p>

  <h2>Editorial Independence</h2>
  <p>FreelancePricingCalc is independently operated. We do not accept payment from freelance platforms, marketplaces, or service providers in exchange for content or referrals. Our editorial team — led by Phoenix Reyes, a 10-year independent contractor — reviews all content for accuracy and updates tax rates and market benchmarks annually. Nothing on this site constitutes financial, legal, or tax advice; consult qualified professionals for your individual situation.</p>
